chapterTitle: The Business AI Myth - Why Most Owners Miss the Real Money
content:
The Seismic Shift You Can’t Ignore Let me be blunt: AI is the biggest seismic shift in business since the internet. Period. And right now, 95% of business owners are screwing it up. They’re sitting on their phones, poking at ChatGPT like it’s a toy. They’re asking it to write emails, make memes, or summarize their Zoom calls. And they think that’s “using AI.” It’s not. That’s like saying you’re a master chef because you learned how to use a microwave. Meanwhile, a handful of smart entrepreneurs are packaging AI into strategic advisory offers that sell for $2,500, $5,000, even $10,000 a month. They’re cashing checks while everyone else wastes time with prompts. AI isn’t about playing with tools. It’s about printing cash. If you miss that point, you’re already losing.   The Trap: Chasing Tools Instead of Profit Here’s the fatal mistake almost everyone makes: they chase tools. One week it’s ChatGPT. Next week it’s some workflow automation in Zapier. Then they’re obsessing over a voice clone tool, a bot builder, or the latest AI Chrome extension. It feels productive. It feels like you’re staying on top of the game. But all you’re doing is chasing shiny objects while the money passes you by. Let me make this crystal clear: your clients don’t give a damn about your tool stack. They don’t care if you’re using ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, or some obscure AI you found on Product Hunt. What they care about is results. They care about outcomes. They care about growing their business, reducing wasted time, and crushing their competitors. If you sell AI as a pile of tools, you’re dead. Tools commoditize. There will always be somebody cheaper, faster, and shinier. But if you sell AI as a system - a path from pain to profit - you win. The “Stack” Obsession I’ve been coaching MSPs for years, and I see this same obsession with “the stack” all the time. You tell them to raise their prices, to 3x or 5x what they charge, and the first thing out of their mouth is, “What’s in the stack?” They can’t get out of their tool-junkie mindset. So I flip it on them. I ask: “If you had unlimited budget for every client, would you give them the cheapest option, the mid-tier option, or the best damn offer you could build?” Every single time, they say, “The best.” Exactly. So why would you sell anything else? The same is true with AI. Don’t waste your life trying to assemble some magical “AI tool stack.” That’s not what makes you valuable. Your value is in defining the best strategy for the business in front of you. Not the cheapest toolset. Not the middle-tier option. The best. Strategy Beats Tech Every Time Let’s be real: most of you reading this aren’t coders. And that’s fine. You don’t need to be. You don’t need to know how to build AI models, deploy machine learning pipelines, or manage APIs. You need to know how to sell strategy. Think about it like this: I pay a tax strategist. Not a bookkeeper. Not a CPA who files my taxes. A strategist. This person doesn’t touch a single form. They don’t crunch receipts. They don’t “do” taxes. Instead, they sit at 36,000 feet and advise. They tell me what moves to make, what entities to set up, how to save millions, and what to avoid. Then they point me to the people who can execute - a CPA, a bookkeeper, a payroll service. They don’t do. They direct. That’s exactly what you’re doing with AI. You are the strategist. The Fractional AI Officer. The one at 36,000 feet painting the picture, setting the roadmap, and saying, “Here’s how AI is going to make you more money.” You don’t need to build the tool. You don’t need to code the workflow. You need to own the strategy. Imposter Syndrome Will Kill You Let me hit another raw truth: most people won’t even start because they’re scared they don’t “know enough.” “I’ve only used ChatGPT. I’m not an AI expert.” “I’ve never built an automation. How could I advise someone?” Listen. Clients don’t need you to be a PhD in machine learning. They need you to be one step ahead of them. That’s it. And trust me - you already are. Most business owners know less than nothing about AI. They’ve heard the buzz, maybe played with ChatGPT, and that’s it. They’re confused, overwhelmed, and afraid of falling behind. That confusion is your opportunity. Confidence is what wins. I’ve watched people with zero AI delivery experience walk into a meeting and crush it because they had conviction. They spoke with authority. They positioned themselves as the guide. If you walk in apologizing for what you don’t know, you’re dead. If you walk in saying, “I am your AI strategist. I’m here to show you where the profit is,” you win. Confidence closes. Period. Why the Fractional AI Officer Wins You might be wondering, “Why call it a Fractional AI Officer?” Because it works. Small and mid-sized businesses already know the language of “fractional.” They’ve heard of fractional CFOs, fractional CMOs, fractional sales leaders. It signals authority. It signals strategy. It signals that you’re an executive-level advisor, not a tool jockey.

Every AI decision flows through you. This is how you make your first $1M with AI. Not by building bots. Not by tinkering with workflows. But by positioning yourself as the trusted advisor, selling clarity, and owning the strategy. Tools don’t make you money. Offers do. That’s the business AI myth - and now you know better. So let’s move on and talk about how to package your Strategic AI Offer so you can start cashing in.

content:
Chapter 2: Strategy vs. Tech – Why You Don't Need to Code

The Lie That's Holding You Back

The biggest lie out there right now is this:

"To make money with AI, you need to be technical."

I don't care if you can't code. I don't care if you've never touched an API. I don't care if the last time you built something technical was making a MySpace page in 2006.

The people making the most money with AI right now aren't the coders. They're the strategists.

They're the ones packaging the vision, not the tools. They're the ones walking into boardrooms saying, "Here's how AI will unlock $2M in growth for your business."

And guess what? Not one CEO has ever stopped me mid-pitch to ask if I could code Python. They don't give a shit. They want profit, not programming.

Strategy Is What Businesses Actually Pay For

Let's cut the fluff: business owners do not want more tools. They already drown in tools.

They've got CRMs they don't use. They've got project management apps with empty boards. They've got half-baked marketing platforms collecting dust.

They don't need another tool. They need a strategy.

Think about it. When you hire a financial advisor, do you care if they can code Excel macros? No. You care if they can grow your wealth.

When you hire a personal trainer, do you care if they wrote the textbook on exercise science? No. You care if they can get your ass in shape.

Same with AI. Clients don't pay for tools. They pay for strategy that leads to results.

chapterTitle: Strategy vs. Tech - Why You Don't Need to Code
content:
The General Contractor Analogy

Stop thinking like a laborer. Start thinking like a general contractor.

When you build a house, who makes the most money? It's not the electrician. It's not the plumber. It's the GC - the general contractor.

The GC doesn't pick up a hammer. They don't install the toilet. They don't wire the lights. They own the vision, they hire the subs, and they manage the project. And they walk away with the biggest check.

That's you in the AI world. You're the general contractor. You don't swing the hammer. You direct the project. You make sure all AI decisions flow through you.

If the client needs a workflow automated, fine. Bring in a tool guy. If they need data cleaned, fine. Bring in a data nerd. But you? You stay at 36,000 feet. You stay in charge of the money and the strategy.

That's how you build a $1M AI advisory business.

Let me explain why coders and tool junkies are screwed.

AI is evolving too damn fast. What you code today will be irrelevant in 90 days. The big players - OpenAI, Microsoft, Google - are absorbing every feature and giving it away for free.

I've seen people spend six months coding an AI scheduling assistant. Guess what? Microsoft Teams now has one built in. That entire project was dead on arrival.

You will never out-build the billion-dollar vendors. But you can out-sell them. You can out-position them. You can translate their chaos into strategy for businesses who are lost.

Coders get commoditized. Strategists get paid.

chapterTitle: Strategy vs. Tech - Why You Don't Need to Code
content:
The Fractional AI Officer Role

This is why I keep hammering the Fractional AI Officer title.

It's not some gimmick. It's a positioning play. Businesses already understand fractional CFOs, fractional CMOs, fractional sales leaders. They know these people bring strategy without the cost of a full-time executive.

When you call yourself a Fractional AI Officer, you instantly elevate yourself. You're not a freelancer. You're not a tool jockey. You're an executive-level strategist.

That one positioning shift changes everything:

- You can charge $2,500–$10,000/month instead of $50/hour.
- You get long-term contracts (24–36 months), not one-off projects.
- You own the client relationship, not the tool vendors.

Let me drive this home with a personal story.

I pay a tax strategist. Not a bookkeeper. Not a CPA. A strategist.

This person doesn't file my taxes. They don't touch QuickBooks. They don't reconcile a single statement.

What they do is tell me where to put my money. They structure my entities. They find loopholes. They save me six figures a year - legally.

And I pay them very well for it.

That's what you become when you step into the Fractional AI Officer role. You're not the person pushing buttons. You're the person who tells the client which buttons matter - and why.

Here's another trap: "But someone has to execute!"

Yes. And that someone doesn't have to be you.

content:

The execution layer is cheap. The strategy layer is expensive.

Let go of execution. Own the strategy. That's where the leverage lives.

Look - I'm not anti-tech. If you love coding and want to build tools, go for it. But don't confuse building with earning.

Building is a hobby. Earning is a business.

If you're reading this book, I assume you want to build a $1M+ business. That means your job is to sell, position, and strategize - not to tinker in Python all day.

Chapter 3: The $100K Offer Stack – What to Sell and How to Price It

Here's a hard truth: most people who try to sell AI services fail not because they lack skill - but because they have no idea what they're actually selling.

They show up to calls saying things like:

"I do automation and chatbots."

And then they wonder why no one pulls out their credit card.

The problem isn't the market. The problem is the offer. If your offer is vague, your results will be vague. If your pricing is random, your income will be random.

This chapter is about fixing that - permanently.

2. Marketing – Content takes forever to create. Campaigns are generic. Nobody's testing offers fast enough.

Every business has one or more of these gaps. Your job is to expose them.

chapterTitle: The $100K Offer Stack - What to Sell and How to Price It
content:
This is your Trojan Horse. You charge $1,000–$5,000 for it, and it's how you walk in the door, earn authority, and set yourself up for the retainer.

The AIGPA framework is simple:

1. Stakeholder Interview – Sit down with the owner/execs. Ask them:
   - Where are you bleeding time?
   - Where are you missing revenue?
   - What's keeping you up at night?
   - Where are competitors beating you?

2. Process Mapping – Look at how they actually do things. Sales calls, onboarding, customer service, marketing campaigns, finance. Map the flow.

3. Gap Analysis – Spot the friction. "Here's where you lose leads. Here's where you waste hours. Here's where you fail to follow up."

4. Monetize the Gap – Assign a dollar amount. "This process is wasting 50 hours/month at $50/hour = $2,500/month wasted. That's $30K/year gone."

5. Roadmap – Present a plan. "Close these gaps with AI strategy and you unlock $250K in profit over the next year. My advisory fee is $5K/month to make sure you get it."

This is how you sell without selling. You're not pitching tools. You're exposing pain. And people will pay anything to make the pain go away.

You talk to a business owner. They admit their sales team struggles to follow up with leads. Some sit for days before anyone reaches out.

You map it. You show them they're losing 20% of opportunities because of slow follow-up.

That's 780 hours a year. At $40/hour, that's $31,200 wasted every year.

When you show the owner that one simple change could save them $30K+ a year, suddenly your $2,500/month fee feels cheap.

And remember: you don't have to build the solution. You just point it out, roadmap it, and oversee the fix. That's advisory. That's where the money is.

Clients Pay for the Translation, Not the Tools

Here's something I need you to get through your head: business owners aren't stupid. They know AI is out there. They just don't know how to apply it.

They're overwhelmed by noise. ChatGPT, Copilot, Claude, Jasper, MidJourney, endless tools - they don't know what matters.

You're not selling tools. You're selling translation.

You're the one saying: "Forget the noise. Here's the two things that actually move the needle in your business. Here's what it's worth. Here's the plan."

Now, let me warn you: do not turn this into a cookie-cutter checklist.

Too many people want a "step-by-step" AI stack they can slap on every client. That doesn't work.

chapterTitle: The $100K Offer Stack - What to Sell and How to Price It
content:
Every business is different. Their goals are different. Their processes are different. Their gaps are different.

Yes, your sales process is static (FTA → AIGPA → retainer). That never changes. But your recommendations are dynamic. They adapt to the business in front of you.

That's why you're valuable. You're not a robot spitting out the same advice. You're the strategist tailoring the roadmap to the client.

Monetizing the Gap = Closing the Deal

Here's the secret: once you put a dollar amount on the gap, the deal is basically closed.

Business owners make decisions with their wallets. If you say, "You're wasting time," they shrug. If you say, "You're losing $250K/year," they pay attention.

Your advisory fee becomes irrelevant compared to the savings or profit they unlock.

That's the close. That's how you sell without being "salesy." You just show them the math.

Case Study: The Power of the Gap

One of our clients ran their first AI Growth & Profit Assessment.

They discovered the company was losing roughly $400K/year in missed leads and inefficiencies.

They walked back in and said: "You're bleeding $400K/year. I'll oversee the fix for $5,000/month."

The client signed immediately. Because $60K/year for a Fractional AI Officer is nothing compared to saving $400K.

That's the power of the Profit Gap.
